Every time sport defeats disadvantage, everyone wins.  For 20 years, we’ve believed that sport powerfully unites us and can uniquely engage young people and children; through sport, millions have been able to access the change programmes they’ve desperately needed to help move their lives forwards.  Together with Laureus Sport For Good, the programmes we support tackle the most challenging social problems frustrating the futures of young people and children in our local communities: health and mental wellbeing; access to education; women and girl’s equality; employability; inclusivity for the marginalized; and ending violence.  #Laureus #SportforGood #Everyonewins #Changethegameforkids #MercedesBenz

In 1957, the 300 SL Roadster replaced the "Gullwing" coupé. The single-joint swing axle introduced in the "Ponton" six-cylinder models of the W 180 series in 1954 was adopted in an adapted form and fitted with a compensating spring for the first time. The innovative MBUX Hyperscreen offers both drivers and front-seat passengers completely new ways of control, interaction and entertainment. Its “zero-layer principle” automatically brings all apps and functions into a fluid, proactive user interface – powered by an AI that delivers a seamless human-machine interaction and learns the driver’s preferences and behaviors to anticipate various driving situations. #MercedesBenz #MBUX #hyperscreen

The MBUX Hyperscreen is a milestone in the merging of analogue and digital design. As the largest free-form glass surface there has ever been in a Mercedes-Benz, it not only offers an electrifying look but also a new level visual clarity that is paired with an extremely emotional visualization.  Learn more: mb4.me/mb-hyperscreen

When it comes to its design, the MBUX Hyperscreen sets new standards, as it's an outstanding example of the fusion of digital and analogue design: multiple displays merge into one to create an impressive curved screen surface. The most aesthetic, the most intelligent and the most intuitive there has ever been: the all-new MBUX Hyperscreen with “Zero Layer” function is a car display unlike any other.  Learn more: mb4.me/mb-hyperscreen #MercedesBenz #MBUX #hyperscreen

With the “Zero Layer”, the MBUX Hyperscreen creates an entirely new level of user interaction and assistance. At any given time, it neatly arranges all necessary information on the personalized top layer – from navigation to calls and messaging to massage. And as the adaptive AI is always learning, the Hyperscreen continuously optimizes its suggestions.  Learn more: mb4.me/mb-hyperscreen

We are proud to say that the MBUX Hyperscreen is the new benchmark in intuitive user experience on the road. Acting as the centre of attention, control, and entertainment in the Mercedes-Benz of the future, it fully reinvents how we interact with our cars.  Learn more: mb4.me/mb-hyperscreen

The roadster had a further developed chassis, later it was fitted with disc brakes and an engine block made of cast aluminum. The elegant, open sports car also had the will to compete: Paul O'Shea won the American sports car championship of 1957 in category D with the 300 SLS, which was based on the production version.  via Mercedes-Benz Museum #MBclassic #300SLroadster #sportscar #supercar #MercedesBenz

😎  On September 2nd we introduced the new S-Class! Each of its predecessors marked the very forefront of modern technology. Originally introduced in the spring of 1954, the Type 220 was the first Mercedes-Benz six-cylinder model in a self-supporting design and featured a previously unknown level of comfort. Safe driving characteristics were guaranteed by the single-joint swing axle, which the Type 220 introduced to series production automotive engineering. With the arrival of the revised, more powerful Type 220 S (74 kW/100 PS) in 1956, the letter “S” made its permanent entry into the nomenclature of the Mercedes-Benz luxury class and underlined the special class status of the “Ponton” six-cylinder.  via Mercedes-Benz Museum #MBclassic #MercedesBenz #ponton #Sclass #mercedesbenzclassic #ClassicCar

On September 2nd we introduced the new S-Class! Each of its predecessors marked the very forefront of modern technology. In 1981, the airbag, now a central element of automotive safety, first made its way into series production in the S-Class from the 126 series. The driver’s airbag was initially combined with a pyrotechnic belt tensioner for the passenger seat. Beginning in 1988, Mercedes-Benz also offered its customers a passenger airbag. As part of a major model update in the fall of 1985, all S-Class models with gasoline engines were equipped with a regulated three-way catalytic converter on request.  #MBmuseum #W126 #MercedesBenz #mercedesbenzclassic #ClassicCar

In September we will introduce the new S-class! Each of its predecessors marked the very forefront of modern technology. The "finnie" models 220, 220 S and 220 SE (W 111), introduced in 1959, were named after the discreet tail fins that adorn the rear fenders. This new Mercedes-Benz luxury class generation was a very special milestone in automotive history as it represented the first time that the safety body with a rigid passenger cell and crumple zones at the front and rear had been implemented in a production car, thereby better protecting the occupants. In 1961, the 300 SE (W 112) was launched as the top model in the 300 SE model series. In 1963, the 300 SE long version established the tradition of Mercedes-Benz's luxury long sedans: the ten centimeter longer wheelbase provided rear-seat passengers significantly more legroom and travel comfort.  mb4.me/MBmuseum  Mercedes-Benz Museum #MBclassic #MercedesBenz #Sclass #W111 #W112

This beautiful Mercedes-Benz 280 SE 3.5 Cabriolet can be found in our #alltimestars showroom in Stuttgart, Germany. In August 1961, a convertible version of the 220 SEb was presented, which was an exact replica of the coupé-variant except for the absent roof and required body stiffening. This elegant and representative model became the successor of the 128 series convertible, which after October 1960 had been produced no longer. From a technical and stylistic point of view, the new model was derived from the 220 SEb saloon, which was presented in August 1959, and was also assigned to model series 111. In contrast to their predecessors, the coupé and convertible variants were planned as a fully-fledged four-seated models. Enjoy this one virtually in a quiet #museummomentofzen. We stay with you!  📸 by Ranier Fernandez Photography via Mercedes-Benz Museum

We want to keep you safe. Safety and trust are matters of the heart for us at Mercedes-Benz.  However, the safety systems of our vehicles can't protect our family and friends from the current health situation. To #flattenthecurve, we need to do more. That's why we have decided to put on hold the production and administration in the majority of our European facilities.   To stay safe, please try to stay at home. In the meantime, we will devote our social media channels on Facebook, Instagram and LinkedIn to make #socialdistancing as easy as possible for you as well as to share important information from health institutes and agencies. So stay tuned – and #flattenthecurve.  📷 Ranier Fernandez Photography for #MBSocialCar

The GLS (2019) offers space for living large. The increased wheelbase not only makes getting in and out easy but also provides impressive head- and legroom. In addition, the seats in the second row can be electronically adjusted by up to ten centimeters.  The third seat row of the new GLS offers plenty of room for friends and family to sit comfortably up to a height of 1.94 m. And at the touch of a button, the seven-seater turns from a luxury saloon into a cargo champion. With its maximum loading capacity of 2,400 liters, you don’t need to make many compromises.   In the GLS (2019), luxury doesn't stop in the front. The Rear Comfort Package Plus lets you enjoy Multicontour seats with massage function as well as the MBUX infotainment system in the rear area of the GLS. The various comforts can be easily controlled via a built-in Android tablet.  http://mb4.me/gls-com_fbk

Béla Barényi is the pioneer of passive automotive security systems. With his 2500 patents, he enabled Mercedes to heighten the standard of road safety already in the mid-1900s. Many of them went into series production for the first time on the W 111, the famous “fintail”.   In 1980, Karl-Heinz Baumann former Head of Mercedes-Benz Passive Safety followed up Barényi’s legacy with a first sketch of the automatic roll bar. The revolutionary safety feature premiered in the Mercedes-Benz R 129 only 9 years later.   See the journey to modern safety laid out in the current issue of Classic Magazine.   mbmag.me/ios mbmag.me/android

To date, more than 14,000 cars have been tested. Since 2016, around 900 crash tests plus around 1,700 “sled tests” have been carried out at the Technology Centre for Vehicle Safety (TFS) in Sindelfingen – all in the name of safety. Mercedes-Benz consistently set new standards for crash test procedures and testing facilities, thus sustainably improved vehicle safety in the interests of all road users on a lasting basis. More info here: http://mb4.me/60YC
